    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because it's lighter-bodied with moderate tannins and bright acidity that won't overwhelm the palate. The grape's transparency means you can taste differences between regions and producers more easily, making it educational for developing your palate. Start with accessible regions like Willamette Valley or Central Otago, which offer excellent quality-to-price ratios and approachable fruit-forward styles.</p>
